```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return Math.abs(log - Math.round(log)) < 1e-10;
    }
}
```

This solution works by calculating the logarithm of the given number `n` with base 3. If `n` is a power of three, then the result of this calculation will be an integer. However, due to floating-point precision issues, we need to check if the result is close enough to an integer. We do this by comparing the absolute difference between the result and its rounded value to a small threshold (1e-10 in this case). If the difference is less than the threshold, we consider the number to be a power of three.

This solution has a time complexity of O(1) since it only involves a few arithmetic operations and a comparison. It also has a space complexity of O(1) since it only uses a constant amount of space to store the intermediate results.

Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
